But I'll be voting against most of the other ballot measures (even ones I agree with!), because I believe these are matters that are best determined by the state legislators you elected to represent your interests, after they closely and carefully review the issues at play. 12/12

So I'll be voting for Proposition 1, because I think it's important that we establish state constitutional protections against federal attacks on reproductive rights following the Supreme Court's decision in Dobbs... 11/

But I would urge you to think about when and where you want to limit our discretion. 

In general, unless you both agree with the policy AND also believe it's necessary to tie the hands of future legislatures, I'd recommend voting against the referenda and initiatives. 10/

There are certainly instances in which limiting the flexibility of the Legislature might be considered appropriate or even necessary. For example, many people, myself included, believe limiting the Legislature's ability to raise taxes is an important constraint here in CA. 9/

For example, imagine a cause you care deeply about. Let's say there's a ballot initiative that proposes to spend $10 billion a year for that.

That may sound great, but forces hard tradeoffs. Where do we cut $10b? Public safety? Education? Health care? 8/
Once enacted, these propositions tie the Legislature's hands, in ways that are both intended (by the supporting interest groups) and unintended.  7/

These are decisions that should be thoughtful, and the result of careful, close analysis of the tradeoffs involved. But we have work, families, social lives... most of us don't have the time or energy to engage in this type of effort. 6/

We as voters are expected to make momentous decisions that might be worth billions of dollars to certain groups or industries, based on a short blurb in our voter guide and of course the political ads funded by interest groups. 5/

Often, these ballot propositions are proposed by well funded interest groups who couldn't convince a majority of the legislature to support their cause. They spend tens or even hundreds of millions of dollars on political advertising that is often very misleading. 4/

Initiatives and referenda bypass the Legislature and once passed, become immovable obstacles we cannot change and which can only be amended or repealed by the voters, an incredibly difficult task given the size of our state's voting population. 3/

New proposed laws often have hidden agendas or nuances that are difficult to understand, even with a seasoned staff and close analysis of the issues. As a new(ish) legislator, I can tell you even "simple" bills often have complex issues not obvious on first read. 2/

I'm not making ballot recommendations this year, but I did want to share my thoughts on ballot initiatives and referenda here in CA. 

I think you should vote NO unless you strongly support the policy AND you believe it's necessary to bypass the legislature. 1/

This is a crazy system that encourages massive waste and is totally counterproductive at a time when the entire western US is facing drought due to the effects of climate change. 

Glad to see our state is taking action, but we need a serious federal and regional overhaul. 5/5

This is apparently pretty common. Water districts, esp. those in drought-prone areas, need to ensure adequate supply so they buy up water rights.

But when they have sufficient water supply, they don't want to lose these rights, so they are forced to use their excess water. 4/

I spoke with one local water district that had invested heavily in alfalfa growing operations. When I asked why alfalfa, the answer was that it was particularly water intense so they could use their excess water to grow it. 3/

We have a complex patchwork of different laws, but collectively, these tend to encourage overuse through so-called "use it or lose it" provisions. 2/
